{#
  Example 06 — Follow the OS `prefers-color-scheme`.

  Two ways to do this, and they compose.

  1. `detectFromSystem: true` (used below). The client reads
     `matchMedia("(prefers-color-scheme: dark)")` on init and resolves
     "dark" or "light" — but only if neither `value` nor storage
     already supplied a slug, and only if the resolved slug is one of
     `themes`. No server involvement at all.

     The catch: `matchMedia` does not exist at Nunjucks render time,
     so the macro cannot know the preference. Its server-rendered
     `aria-selected` still resolves from
     `value or defaultValue or "light" or themes[0]`, and the client
     corrects it on init. On a dark-preferring machine that means a
     light first paint, then a swap. The listbox is closed and the
     button inert throughout, so nobody interacts with a control in an
     inconsistent state — but the flash is real.

  2. Resolve it server-side and pass it as `value`, which outranks
     everything else. This is the flicker-free path. Use the Client
     Hint header if your host sends it, or a cookie written from
     `onChange`:

         const prefersDark =
             req.headers["sec-ch-prefers-color-scheme"] === "dark";
         res.render("page.njk", { prefersDark });

     Client Hints require an opt-in response header and the hint is not
     universally supported, so treat it as an optimisation rather than
     a guarantee — `detectFromSystem` stays as the backstop.

  Whichever you use, the user's own pick wins afterwards and persists
  via `storageKey`: storage outranks detection, so a returning visitor
  who chose "light" on a dark-preferring machine keeps "light".

  Spec: spec/index.md §5.2 (resolution order), §5.8 (why detection is
  client-only).
#}
{% from "../theme-select.njk" import themeSelect %}

{{ themeSelect({
    label: "Theme",
    themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
    themes: ["light", "dark"],
    detectFromSystem: true,
    value: serverResolvedTheme | default(""),
    storageKey: "my-app:theme"
}) }}

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit, matchSystemTheme } from "../theme-select.client.js";
    const [controller] = autoInit();

    // `matchSystemTheme` is exported so you can reuse the exact
    // resolution the client uses internally. It returns "" when the
    // preferred slug is not among your themes, and when matchMedia is
    // unavailable — so guard on the empty string rather than on the
    // media query's truthiness.
    if (window.matchMedia) {
        const mql = window.matchMedia("(prefers-color-scheme: dark)");
        mql.addEventListener("change", () => {
            // Tracks OS preference changes live. Note this overrides a
            // choice the user made explicitly; drop the listener if you
            // would rather an explicit pick stick for the session.
            const slug = matchSystemTheme(["light", "dark"]);
            if (slug) controller?.setTheme(slug);
        });
    }
</script>
